  "prompt": "What guidelines are in place regarding passport photos in Canada?",
  "response": "In Canada, there are specific guidelines for passport photos to ensure they meet international standards and can be correctly processed. Here are the general requirements:\n\n1. **Size and Dimensions**: Passport photos must be 50 mm wide by 70 mm high. The face should be in the middle of the photo and sized between 31 mm and 36 mm from chin to crown.\n\n2. **Background**: The background must be white or light-colored and plain. There should be no shadows, patterns, or textures.\n\n3. **Image Quality**: Photos must be clear, sharp, and in focus with no underexposure or overexposure. They should be printed on high-quality photographic paper.\n\n4. **Pose and Expression**: You must face the camera directly with a neutral expression, eyes open and mouth closed. Both ears should be visible if possible.\n\n5. **Head Coverings**: Head coverings are only allowed for religious or medical reasons, and your full facial features from bottom of chin to top of forehead and both edges of the face must be clearly shown.\n\n6. **Glasses**: Tinted glasses and sunglasses are not permitted. If you wear prescription glasses, they must not show glare or have heavy frames.\n\n7. **Lighting**: The photo should be taken with even lighting, to avoid shadows and reflections, especially on the face.\n\n8. **Stories**: The photos must be taken within the last six months to reflect your current appearance.\n\n9. **Digital Alterations**: The photo must not be digitally altered in any way. This includes modifying the background, retouching, or applying filters.\n\n10. **Print and Finish**: Ensure the photo is printed on high-quality photographic paper that will resist fading and features a clear, even finish.\n\nIt\u2019s always a good idea to follow these guidelines closely or use a professional photographer familiar with passport photo requirements to avoid any issues with your application. Additionally, the specifications can be confirmed on the official Government of Canada website or through passport issuing authorities, as they may get updated.",
